In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims October as National Breast Cancer Awareness Month. The article highlights the importance of supporting breast cancer research, educating the public about risk factors, detection, and treatment, and honoring those affected by the disease. It mentions that thanks to advancements in detection and treatment, mortality rates for breast cancer have decreased. The National Institutes of Health, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, and the Department of Defense are investing in breast cancer research. The article emphasizes the importance of knowing the risk factors for breast cancer and maintaining a healthy lifestyle. It also encourages women to undergo regular screenings, such as mammograms, as early detection is crucial for successful treatment. The article mentions that the Affordable Care Act requires health insurance policies to cover preventive services, including mammography screenings, without additional cost. The proclamation concludes by urging individuals and organizations to participate in activities that raise awareness about breast cancer prevention and control.